n. There is also a consensus among experts that a small clique of corrupt political actors has captured most Hungarian state institutions and a significant portion of the business sector. What fostered corruption in Hungary? What are the most typical forms of corruption in this country? What do Hungarians think about it? What is the role of prime minister Viktor Orbán in this? Sociology of Corruption proposes a novel sociological theory of corruption focusing on social status and relationships, network structures, and power dynamics as important explanatory factors of corrupt behavior. Although his focus is on Hungary, Jancsics's findings are applicable to other nations and cultural contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCorruptionxSocial aspectszHungary. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Corruption & Misconduct .2bisacsh  aTransparency, Perceptions, policy, goverment, political dynamics, corrupt political actors, ethnographic fieldwork.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501774331?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501774331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501774331/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles